segments.text: we're not going to bury the makeup of the student body now as far as you know in terms of the students background and their major there is no difference between urban kids and country kids and their participation and ag majors and engineers and so forth is there no
We're working on trying to put together the databases where we can combine all the different things that we do into one database and see how people participate to get a better feel for that.
My guess is we're reaching in all our different programs about 90% of the student body at least one time a year.
If you look at our most active people,
Some of them come from inner city Houston, some of them come from far.
There's nothing out there that some of the most active people that we have today didn't participate in sports at all in high school.
Some of them played all the time.
Our mission right now is really, and the mission statement's sitting there on my desk, but this is how I paraphrase it.
Our job is to give our students, primarily the 18 to 22 year olds, the opportunity to experience a lot of different kinds of things.
We want them to build an active, healthy lifestyle.
That's our mission, and the way we do that is by providing the opportunities.

and for us to be successful we have to provide a lot of different opportunities that's why our program is comprehensive uh what about uh minority students or we if you look at the makeup of the people who participate in our programs uh we're we have more it's pretty close to the same makeup as the university
But in reality, we have more African Americans, more Hispanics, more American Indians, more women than the student body.
Per capita.
Yeah, per capita.
The only place for short is in white males, which is kind of interesting.
Have there been any teams in any of the competition which are minority or international that you know of?

yes especially you know especially in soccer we have a lot of international soccer and they win they usually win they get a little frustrated with the way we officiate because we officiate the way americans officiate soccer and they want us to officiate the way internationals soccer is officiated but they can still win they're good enough to still win it's uh
I suppose the other area that this facility has helped accommodate, and this is, I think, a pretty good anecdote, is the international student.
Because, for instance, we had two hours a week where you could play badminton free play before we moved in here.
Now you could anytime the building's open.
But the sports that are favored by the international students are all

accommodated in this building badminton volleyball soccer table tennis it's here and it's here all the time the of the first 25 bricks we sold and they're welcome champions three of those were international students that's surprising this especially on friday nights this is a home away from home you know they they don't can't go home every weekend like some of our students can
but this is their home away from home.
They've enjoyed it, they've really taken an active part in this building.
Now, I would assume that table tennis or ping pong, which is it called today?
Table tennis.
Table tennis.
I would assume that table tennis might be very keen interest to some international students.
What are some, are there some other sports that you mentioned?
Let's see, what else that are particularly attractive to international?
Soccer.
Soccer.
And there's a wide variety.
a number of countries that are really competitive in soccer.
Volleyball is big with the international students.
Badminton, especially the English and the Indians really like badminton.
You'll see a lot of people playing badminton anytime the building's open.
It's amazing how many badminton players there are.
Squash is European and Asian.
And my brain's not recovering the name of the English baseball.
Cricket.
Cricket.
Do we play cricket now?
We had a cricket sports club one time.
There's some people here that play cricket, but we don't have a facility for it right now.
And we don't play Australian football.
No.
That looks too dangerous to me.
What about, do we play rugby?
Yes.
Rugby is a sports club.
We have 29 teams that participate as if they were varsity teams.
The only difference is their funding level for those 29 teams is about $80,000 a year.

so they're funding a lot they they they're supported primarily by funds out of their own pocket to participate but rugby is one of those and lacrosse there's several of the sports that are fairly competitive contact organizations are there some sports that have been requested that you all have not accommodated uh boxing
We've worked a little bit with boxing, but in reality, that's a really tough one to manage.
It's really too easy to get hurt there.
Any others?
Pushball.
We had an incident in pushball probably the second or third year I was here.
And the way push ball is, this giant ball is about eight foot in diameter and it's filled with air.
On the surface it doesn't seem like it's a dangerous game, but just teams line up and you decide to try to push it across the other person's field.
The way the Corps used to play it is they would start on the goal line with the ball on the 50 yard line and they'd run to the ball.
Of course, what happens is you get this huge pressure exerted on one side and you almost get a kickback effect.
We had a gentleman hurt pretty severely in one of those games.
There's other ways to enjoy sport besides something that can be sedentary.
So we kind of eliminated push ball.
I can't think of any others.
As the years went on, what about the Corps involvement and interest in intramurals?
Did it remain strong or did it decline?
The interest has always been very strong.
What we've tried to do with the Corps
achieve a balance because they are looking at a more balanced approach.
They want people to participate in sports.
They want them to be competitive.
They want them to understand competition in sports.
But they also want them to compete in the classroom.
They want them to get grades that are good enough to get a graduation, get out of here.
So they try to balance that.
At one time, I think we had gone, there's a course on a point system.
and they're competing for, part of the general Moore trophy is points awarded through intervals.
So we, in trying to offer a diverse program,
we put too many points on the points system, then we had to back off a little bit.
And it's primarily now the four major sports plus the two meets that the Corps is competing in.
And they can compete in other things, it's just not for points.
But the problem with the Corps, if we put it on the points system, they have a team.
And Senator Gere was overextending that.
And are the Corps sports co-ed also?
We have...
I wish I knew the answer to that.
I know we started down that road.
Whether we're still doing it or not, I'm not sure.
My problem right now at Haskell is that we went from eight years ago having 12, 13 people on staff, and now we've got 50 people on staff.
Sure, sure.
I'm having trouble keeping up with all that stuff.
Type us this next note.
You can leave out.
I just want to share an anecdote with him.
As of last fall, I think this fall would also be the same, 5% of all undergraduate males at UT were in fraternities, 6% females were in sororities.
The percentages here instead of 5 and 6 are 6 and 14.
We have a higher percentage of undergraduates in fraternity sororities than UT.
We have more corps members than we, I mean more fraternity and sorority members than we have members of the corps.
And I learned not long ago that three of last year's Yale leaders who were corps members were also fraternity members.
And I hadn't thought about that.
So how things are shifting.
You probably recall before you left that there was a big
deal about fraternities, and especially amongst the core.
Oh, yeah.
No, no.
Then of all of the 54 four-year institutions in Texas, public and private, only eight of those have an undergraduate male majority.
We're one of the eight.
So one of the shifts, and nobody can really explain why,
A higher percentage of young women are going to college now than young men.
We're still, and we've had more entering freshmen the last two falls who were women than men.

but then we got transfer uh menil coming in i think so what uh but did i ask about some uh requests for sports that y'all didn't want to offer some activities i can't think of any others that you've just flatly turned down one of the things that that we we have to do

and we've probably done a pretty good job over the years is when we look at a sport you can take football and make it flag football non-contact and a fairly good game fairly safe game so you're taking risk and managing it and putting it in a context that everybody can play this game you try to do that with we have tried to do that with
sports that people have an interest in.
And there's some things that we haven't quite figured out how to do that.
So we hate to say no.
Sometimes we feel like we have to.
But we would rather say, well, let us work on it.
Let's see if we can figure out a way to make this game rugby.
Which sports have had more problems that cause you more difficulty and which are the most free of problems?
Softball is probably the most free of problems.
It's more of a social game.
People don't get as excited about it in general.
Basketball is always the most contentious.
that people are so close together, there's a lot of physical contact in basketball that the game basically says there's no physical contact.
And it's hard to officiate, hard to officiate .
So that's probably the toughest one.
What kinds of injuries have, in those 27 years, have you had to help with?
A lot of them.
A lot of injuries.
Basketball probably, again, provides the most injuries, and most of them are minor, so to speak.
We have had very few major injuries.
I can't even tell you.
When you start having neck injuries and head injuries, we had a female hit in the face with a softball off the bat, and that's pretty close.
That's some reconstructive surgery.
We had a few things like that, but the majority of our injuries are turned ankle, turned knees, then you have the blown out knees, and you have the broken ankles.
So there's quite a variety, but there's a lot of injuries.
We're involved in a high risk, and our job is to try to manage that risk.
to a point where we aren't taking college students who come here to get an education and put them in a situation where they can't go to school because of an injury.
So we've got to try to manage that stuff.
All right.
Go through the presidents you've worked with and indicate their apparent interest in intramurals or lack thereof, beginning with Williams.
Jack Williams was here when it came in.
Because I was pretty young, I'm not sure if I knew we had a relationship at that time.
But most people felt pretty good about him.
He was very supportive.
I sure did.
From what I could tell, especially from John Colas, he was very pleased with me.
Jarvis Miller.
Jarvis Miller was wonderful.
He was so personable.
Now whether he actually got things accomplished for us or not, I'm not sure, but he was very personal.
He always made you feel good about what you were doing.
So that was kind of a nice pat on the back all the time he got from Jarvis Miller.
Chuck Sampson then for a year.
Chuck Sampson was great.
He was the guy, he was just the opposite of Jarvis.
He didn't have a lot of personality on the surface, but I tell you what, he was there helping you.
He was a hard worker and he understood what we did and I'm not sure where that came from, but he understood.
When I went, there were a few times I had a chance to talk to him and he understood things we were talking about.
We didn't have to explain it to him.
He's a bright guy.
Very supportive.
Then Frank Vanderburg.
He was not.
Frank Vandiver, we'd have been better off if he'd stayed at Rice.
And I think our band told him that one day down at Rice Stadium.
And he and John Coles didn't have a good relationship from what I've heard.
All I know is that it was not the best of times for John, probably not the best of times for us.
But in reality, I was far enough removed that
It probably didn't hurt me much.
See, I was his first doctoral student.
Nice guy, but he had no experience at a public institution, except he did his master's degree at Texas.
He got his undergraduate degree by examination.
He never went to class, an organized class, in his life until he began his master's degree at age 16.
Wow.
He finished his Ph.D. in two nine-month years at Tulane
Washington University, St. Louis, then Rice, then here.
Well, Tulane, Wash U, and Rice are very different from here.
And he didn't understand this place.
He didn't.
He didn't understand the need for Student Services Division.
See, he never.
All right, and then I believe Mobley.
He was good.
And he was another guy that really made you feel good about what you were doing for the university.
And I still have a couple of notes from him, different functions that we were together on.
And he was the kind of guy that stopped me right at the note.
And Dean Gage then was the interim.
Yeah, Dean Gage was really good, I thought.
I mean, very friendly guy, seemed to be very supportive.
He was great.
All right, then after Dean Gage, I believe Dr. Bowen.
Dr. Bowen was fantastic.
Great.
He and Dr. Sutton have a good relationship.
old findings that your whole funny stability is so much better than it was before.
I think he's I think he's great manager.
Super intelligent.
Doesn't take him long to understand an issue.
Doesn't have as much personality as some people would like him to have.
But when it gets down to the real issue, can be very supportive.
And has never put me in a situation where I felt bad or felt like he didn't support me.
Sometimes he just forgets to tell you that he does, maybe.
I think student affairs as a whole is 100% better off now than they were 10 years ago.
A lot of that has to do with Ray Bowen.
I think overall we're probably doing better work, too.
Now, you were officially reporting to the Department of what used to be Health and Physical Education.
When did that cease?
It changed in 1980 when Carl Landis retired, and I reported to Leonard Ponder, who was the department head, and he reported to John Koldus for intramurals for recreational sports at that time.
And then he reported to the dean for the rest of the things that went on in the department.
And then when Leonard retired,
I'm trying to recall the year.

That was when, and I don't remember for sure, that was when we went officially over to Student Affairs and did not report to the... Actually, that may have been, we may have been in that relationship until we moved into this building.
All right.
Ninety-five.
All right, and then now?
Now I report to...
to Jan Winifred, who was Associate Vice President for Student Affairs.
But still within Student Affairs.
Yeah.
All right.
Go through the years and show the change in the number of staff.
Oh, I wish my memory was that good.
We had, in 1973, another little story.
As I, the way I recall this, I got a letter later that said I was hired, but as I recall it, I walked out of Carl Landis' office and he had offered me the job.
And at that point in time, the department was, the Intermural Department was the director, full-time secretary, and full-time maintenance person.
And we had some student workers.
Well, when we walked out of Carl Landis' office and the office just outside of his office, there's a gentleman named Jim Dieter.
And he said, by the way, let me introduce you to Jim Dieter.
He's your new assistant director.
Brand new position.
Carl had already offered the job before you offered the job to me, which is okay.
And Jim and I became great friends.
He's a great, great worker.
Now, what was his primary task at that time?
At that time,
You know, really the first year we did everything together, because he was brand new.
He just finished his master's degree, but had not worked in recreational sports specifically.
He'd been in physical education.
So the first year we did everything together, training officials, everything.
From that point on, I became a pretty good delegator.
He basically ran the program.

majority of the programming efforts that next year and then after that we hired another person see we went from so we started with four people our budget was $50,000 hired Jim was the first one then we hired Susan slider the next year in 1974 and we hired John Meyer in 1975 I think it was
Then we hired some graduate assistantships and we had a little trouble with graduate assistantships because most of them were looking for a recreation degree and we really didn't have that here.
So in 1980, I think was a big change, we dropped our graduate assistantship positions and hired three full-time people, which was a big change, a big number in nearly one year.
So we were up to about in the mid 80s about 12 full-time professionals and then some clerical staff.
When we started planning for staffing this facility and the program related to it, we were at 21 full-time people.
That's everybody.
Maintenance workers, support staff,
and professional staff.
We're today at 50 staff.
Most of that growth happened with new programs and increasing what we're doing with facility management with the Student Recreation Center.
But the other part that really causes significant growth is we, in 1998, took over the golf course.

1996 we took over the golf course yeah july of 96 we took over the golf course and that added 10 people so and in the the traditional recreational intramural recreational sports side of the house we went from five to 40 or four to 40 people so tenfold
and then we picked up the golf course and now we're 50 full-time staff.
Our budgets went from $50,000 from 1973 to $9 million this year.
And the source of that funding?
There's two primary sources, student service fees, about $1.6 million, and recreational sports fee, which raises about $4.7 million.
All right, and both of those are from students.
Right.
We generate the rest of it.
What are the sources of that generation?
Intramural entry fees, about $85,000 a year.
Memberships, 300, 350,000.
Memberships for this facility, non-student members.
Guest passes to use this facility is about 180,000.
I mean, there's a long list.
Aerobics is about 85,000.
Locker rental.
Close to $100,000.
The golf course generated $840,000 this last year.
Does the golf course break even?
We made money last year.
Really?
The golf course has been generating some pretty good money, but we've been slowly doing some upgrades.
So we had a plan going in red for about four years in a row.
We actually made money this year, though.
I can show you the bottom line in this black.
We kind of like it.
We'll probably stay there for a while now.
In all, I think we generate $2.3 million.
Describe how this facility came to be, the planning and the key people and the steps to it and all that.
Tell as much of that story as you can.
In 1987, actually we put together a facility,
a needs assessment survey, send it out, get the materials back.
And we may have done that in the fall.
We did the analysis in January.
And I was talking with John Coles.
I said, we have done this study.
And at some point in time, we really ought to go to the students and talk to them about doing a referendum, too.
At that point in time, the state was not building any facilities.
This was 1987.

we weren't going to get any help from from uh dr mccandless at that time because he didn't have any help to give us so we uh we we talked about using student fees to build a building he asked me to go speak to his two student leader groups that he meets with and he's with them every other week with two different groups when he has dinner with them every tuesday night
and went and talked to them and we were talking about doing it a year later and they said, no, let's do it now.
So we, and I don't remember all the names of the people that were involved in that.
We had a great group of student leaders that we worked with.
I need some names in here.

See, to me, one of the pleasant things, pleasant realities, because just like you, I came from another school here, so I'm also a convert, is the comparatively positive reaction of student leaders here, like Fred Heath with the library.
They endorsed increasing their fee to keep upgrading the library.
And I'm thinking, hooray, hooray, that kind of trust.
They really are.
Yeah, here's the list.
These are the students that attend the meeting.
Mike Sims, student body president.
David McDowell, president of RHA.
Carl Wilkinson, Corps Commander.
Bobby Beiser, president of the MSC.
Remember him?
He's still around.
Helen Delafont, Carolyn Brown, graduate student council, prison senior class.
Marty Holmes, the all-in-group.
Frank Rhodes, University Department Counsel, Scott Mandel, President of Campus Studies, Warren Steffi, editor of the battalion, and he was one of our biggest supporters.
Of course, it's unusual for a student to be editor of the paper each year.
Biggest problem.
And this is what year?
We met with student leaders on February 12, 1987.
Now, you invited them...
Actually, they meet all the time.
They met all the time with Dr. Coles and they invited me.
I did this presentation.
I said, we're thinking about doing this referendum next year.
I'm taking it to the legislature the year after that.
And they said, let's do the referendum now.
So what that meant was.
Do you remember the approximate vote?
Yes, I can tell you exactly.
62.8% in favor.
My, my.
So almost two to one.
Yeah.
The interesting thing was we decided to do a, instead of having the Student Senate put it on the ballot, to do a petition.
And that was part of, of course, the advertising campaign in reality.
So we did this petition, got signatures.
We had it turned into Friday before spring break.
That gave us Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, spring break to plan our campaign and start putting materials together.
And then we had Monday through Friday,
and then Monday of the next week and Tuesday and Wednesday, but polling was over Tuesday and Wednesday, so we had those eight days to actually do the campaign.
What were the contentions of the opponents?
We really didn't have anybody come out and form a no vote.
In reality, I think some people just were concerned that going from zero to 50 bucks, I'd say it's a pretty big increase.

It's interesting because we just had a referendum this last spring and what we told the students basically that we would like to be able to keep what we have and in order to afford that we need to do this.
So we didn't offer them anything new and we actually raised the price by $7.
And we had a 68% positive vote on that one.
Now the fee originally was to...
